<TEXT>
here is the text of the democratic response to 
president reagans radio address saturday given by sen sam nunn 
dga 
good afternoon 
americas defense and foreign policy can only be successful when 
it is supported by a bipartisan consensus in the congress we are 
reminded of this truth by the withdrawal of soviet forces from 
afghanistan and the recent ratification of the intermediate nuclear 
forces treaty 
these achievements were not merely coincidences the courageous 
afghan resistance to soviet invaders was supported by two 
presidents and by a strong bipartisan consensus in the congress 
the important steps leading to the inf treaty were started by the 
carter administration and pursued with determination by the reagan 
administration with consistent support from republicans and 
democrats in congress 
on the other hand disarray in our defense and foreign policy 
has usually been the product of a divided congress and a divided 
america and can often be traced to irresponsible positions taken 
during presidential campaigns our nations failure to deploy a 
survivable landbased missile as well as the delays and costly 
mistakes made in deploying a new penetrating bomber and especially 
our inconsistent and unsuccessful policy in central america are 
vivid examples 
this week president reagans veto of the national defense 
authorization bill represents another serious setback to building a 
bipartisan consensus regarding americas national security policy 
although vice president bush clearly was anxious to toss 
national defense into the political arena i had hoped that 
president reagan would place national security above partisan 
considerations 
i had hoped that president reagan would listen to those who 
urged him not to veto this important bill including his secretary 
of defense his national security adviser and key republican 
members of congress who are experts on national defense like sen 
john warner sen strom thurmond sen ted stevens sen bill cohen 
and sen jake garn unfortunately the president followed the advice 
not of his national security team but rather of vice president 
bushs political team he made this decision without consulting a 
single democrat in the congress 
we will continue to work for the enactment of this important 
defense bill but it will not be easy to put humptydumpty back 
together again congress must be clearly told who speaks for the 
president on national security matters i am confident that we can 
develop a bill that is acceptable to president reagans secretary 
of defense and his national security adviser but i do not believe 
we can reach agreement with the vice presidents political pollster 
and his campaign manager 
the challenge before us however is much broader than simply 
getting this important bill enacted 
if we are to safeguard our nations security we must insist on 
clarity and common sense in our security strategy toughminded 
management of the pentagon measures to reduce the risk of war a 
greater sharing of the burden of defense by our allies and a 
foreign policy grounded in respect for our constitution and our 
basic values 
the next president must appoint experienced capable managers 
who will insist on getting our moneys worth every defense dollar 
spent it takes more than a cash register to run an efficient and 
effective pentagon and it takes more than an adding machine to 
formulate a sound strategy and to set realistic priorities 
in recent years too many tax dollars have been wasted because we 
have produced too many procurement scandals and too few effective 
weapons 
we must also call for a new relationship with our allies to 
achieve a more equitable sharing of defense tasks and to improve 
our common defense through sensible specialization 
finally we must recognize that americas power rests not on 
military might alone but on a competitive economy a solvent 
government an educated people and above all on the democratic 
principles that we exemplify to the world 
as the campaign heats up and the political rhetoric inevitably 
increases i hope that we will remember that our national security 
is too important to be the hostage of partisan politics the late 
sen scoop jackson said it best when he said in matters of 
national security the best politics is no politics 
thank you and have a nice weekend 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

