government control over the economy and attracting private foreign 
investment which has been forbidden 
but diplomats in rangoon and visitors to the capital in recent 
days say burmese businessmen appear to be skeptical of the proposed 
measures and fear another demonetization of the currency as a 
simplistic way to deal with inflation 
the government last fall suddenly withdrew several currency 
notes from circulation without compensation sparking riots and 
talk among burmese that the government had engaged in official 
robbery 
some businessmen reportedly say that the 64yearold sein lwin 
may push the reforms through in order to cling to power but believe 
there will be little followup to the measures since the former 
military officer is considered an old guard socialist 
once regarded as a potential economic power in southeast asia 
burmas influence slipped under sein lwins predecessor 
over the past year conditions have worsened and burma with an 
annual per capita income of less than 200 and a 4 billion debt 
was forced to apply to the united nations for least developed 
developing country status 
although the state in principle supports providing basic food 
supplies to its people through governmentrun stores and 
cooperatives the population has had to rely in recent years on a 
vast black market stocked with items smuggled from other asian 
countries 
