a powerful earthquake rocked eastern 
india bangladesh and burma early saturday triggering landslides 
damaging buildings and sending residents fleeing from their homes 
news reports and witnesses said 
no deaths were immediately reported but at least five people 
were slightly injured when buildings collapsed in indias manipur 
and assam states both areas are hilly but are heavily populated in 
valleys 
people ran out of their houses and started praying said b 
goswami a resident in the town of guwahati contacted by 
telephone guwahati in assam state is about 900 miles east of new 
delhi 
in parts of calcutta women blew conch shells an ancient indian 
tradition believed to appease the weather gods according to the 
press trust of india news agency 
the quake which began at 609 am and registered 73 on the 
richter scale lasted for more than two minutes according to the 
seismological observatory in new delhi 
about eight hours later an earthquake registering 63 on the 
richter scale jolted parts of pakistan and nepal and was felt in 
new delhi according to the earthquake center at the pakistani 
meteorological department no injuries or damage were immediately 
reported 
the new delhi observatory said the epicenter of the first quake 
was in an isolated hilly region in neighboring burma about 15 
miles from the border more than 1000 miles east of the indian 
capital 
tremors were also felt in dhaka the capital of neighboring 
bangladesh but there were no reports of casualties or damage 
property damage and brief power outages were reported in 
manipur assam and nagaland states 
in imphal the capital of manipur about 75 miles from the 
epicenter two people were slightly injured when part of a building 
collapsed press trust said 
in tiniali bam in assam state three people were hurt when a 
house collapsed 
the united news of india reported the roof of a hindu temple in 
the town of sibsagar in assam collapsed and some adjoining 
buildings had cracks and shattered windows 
the quake also triggered landslides in parts of assam forcing 
suspension of train service press trust said 
the epicenter of the second quake was about 280 miles northeast 
of islamabad in the hindu kush mountains of afghanistan and 
northern pakistan according to the earthquake center at the 
pakistani meteorological department 
earthquakes in eastern india are frequent according to hn 
srivastava the director of the seismological observatory in new 
delhi no major quakes have occurred in the region in recent years 
but an earthquake in 1950 killed about 300 people in assam 
the richter scale gauges the energy released by an earthquake as 
measured by ground motion recorded on a seismograph every increase 
of one number means a tenfold increase in magnitude 
a quake of magnitude 7 is considered a major earthquake capable 
of widespread damage in populated areas 
a quake measuring 73 in quetta in what is now pakistan killed 
more than 30000 people on may 31 1935 
